WEBVTT

00:00.920 --> 00:02.221
[bird squawks]

00:02.246 --> 00:03.963
Have you seen my coat?

00:03.988 --> 00:05.416
It's right here.

00:05.442 --> 00:08.622
- Don't touch that. Get away, get away.
- [laughs softly]

00:08.647 --> 00:10.478
It's really taking to you.

00:10.503 --> 00:11.790
Ha, funny.

00:11.815 --> 00:13.446
No, he really has.

00:13.623 --> 00:15.425
It's because I'm the one with the food.

00:15.450 --> 00:16.931
That's why I took to you.

00:16.956 --> 00:18.551
Really?

00:19.184 --> 00:21.442
That mean if I feed you some seeds

00:21.467 --> 00:23.154
you'll forget about
teaching this course?

00:23.180 --> 00:25.467
And miss two months in Bethesda?

00:25.815 --> 00:28.708
It's the vacation capital
of Montgomery County.

00:28.800 --> 00:31.135
[squawks] Get away, get away.

00:31.160 --> 00:32.864
[laughs softly]

00:32.889 --> 00:35.025
Don't touch that. Get away.

00:35.050 --> 00:37.751
[laughter]

00:40.324 --> 00:41.759
[bird squawks]

00:41.784 --> 00:43.567
Hmm.

00:48.622 --> 00:51.151
They charge you twice
for your cable again?

00:51.851 --> 00:54.352
No, I got offered a job.

00:54.377 --> 00:55.592
Yeah? That's great.

00:55.617 --> 00:56.941
I guess.

00:56.966 --> 00:58.432
It's in California.

00:58.457 --> 01:00.423
Oh.

01:00.449 --> 01:02.417
But I mean, that's okay, right?

01:02.442 --> 01:04.352
It's nice out there.

01:04.378 --> 01:07.004
Yeah, definitely.

01:08.862 --> 01:12.273
It's just... just far.

01:12.762 --> 01:14.072
Have you heard from Rush yet?

01:14.097 --> 01:15.298
Northwestern?

01:15.323 --> 01:17.167
Uh, still waiting.

01:17.192 --> 01:19.748
Course, there's always a chance
things could work out here.

01:19.773 --> 01:21.225
Very slim chance.

01:21.250 --> 01:22.085
Hey, you two.

01:22.110 --> 01:23.016
Patients incoming.

01:23.041 --> 01:24.311
You're going to Treatment 6.

01:24.336 --> 01:25.615
April, you got this?

01:25.640 --> 01:26.999
- Yeah.
- Thank you.

01:27.024 --> 01:28.945
Right here.

01:28.970 --> 01:30.101
What do we got?

01:30.126 --> 01:31.740
Chuck Gleason, 42-year-old male.

01:31.765 --> 01:33.800
Found at the bottom of
some stairs on Lower Wacker

01:33.825 --> 01:35.980
with a fractured left tibia.

01:36.005 --> 01:37.598
Okay, on my count.

01:37.623 --> 01:39.491
One, two, three.

01:39.516 --> 01:40.849
Oh.

01:40.874 --> 01:42.225
He looks dehydrated.

01:42.250 --> 01:43.517
Let's call ortho and start some fluids.

01:43.542 --> 01:44.239
- Oh.
- On it.

01:44.264 --> 01:45.425
Starter 1, let's get him set up.

01:45.450 --> 01:47.618
Let's pull the board out.

01:47.643 --> 01:49.361
You got a drink, April?

01:49.387 --> 01:51.748
Could really use a drink.

01:52.023 --> 01:53.522
Are you guys friends?

01:53.547 --> 01:54.981
Frequent flier.

01:55.006 --> 01:56.038
Alcohol.

01:56.063 --> 01:57.398
And everything that goes with it.

01:57.423 --> 01:58.847
How 'bout you, buddy?

01:58.872 --> 02:00.168
You got a drink?

02:00.193 --> 02:02.755
Unfortunately,
this is a hospital, not a bar.

02:02.781 --> 02:04.003
When did this happen?

02:04.028 --> 02:04.776
Yesterday.

02:04.801 --> 02:05.542
Oh.

02:05.567 --> 02:07.246
101.

02:07.271 --> 02:09.137
All right, let's get a
chest X-ray and a UA.

02:09.162 --> 02:10.306
- Okay.
- [groans]

02:10.332 --> 02:12.314
Okay, Mr. Gleason,
you broke your leg pretty bad.

02:12.339 --> 02:13.975
We're gonna have to
evaluate this and...

02:14.000 --> 02:15.465
- He's seizing.
- Mr. Gleason?

02:15.490 --> 02:16.738
All right, milligram of Ativan.

02:16.763 --> 02:18.484
- On it.
- It's a grand mal seizure.

02:18.508 --> 02:19.542
He ever had this before?

02:19.567 --> 02:20.974
Not that I've seen.

02:20.999 --> 02:23.055
Milligram of Ativan.

02:23.952 --> 02:25.838
He's withdrawing.

02:25.863 --> 02:28.683
He's going into delirium tremens.

02:28.708 --> 02:29.911
You know.

02:29.936 --> 02:32.031
Never seen him get DTs before.

02:32.056 --> 02:33.542
It's gonna be bad, isn't it?

02:33.567 --> 02:34.943
Is it ever good?

02:34.968 --> 02:37.790
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

02:38.094 --> 02:39.395
[sighs]

02:39.420 --> 02:41.456
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:41.790 --> 02:45.990
- Synced and corrected by martythecrazy -
- www.addic7ed.com -

02:47.744 --> 02:50.650
- Hey. Thanks for the bird.

02:50.675 --> 02:52.120
Kids are gonna love it.

02:52.379 --> 02:54.414
Definitely. Glad he'll have a nice home.

02:54.439 --> 02:56.424
Yeah. Anything I need to know?

02:56.904 --> 02:57.905
Nope.

02:57.930 --> 02:59.264
Just enjoy.

02:59.289 --> 03:00.727
All right, you're a good man, Doc.

03:00.752 --> 03:02.227
[chuckles]

03:02.252 --> 03:05.766
[siren wails in distance]

03:05.791 --> 03:09.430
Cirrhosis, hepatitis,
cardiomyopathy, renal failure.

03:09.455 --> 03:10.425
Reads like the index

03:10.450 --> 03:11.974
of "Harrison's Guide
to Internal Medicine."

03:11.998 --> 03:13.493
[retches]

03:13.518 --> 03:15.353
[panting]

03:16.490 --> 03:17.842
Ah.

03:17.867 --> 03:19.805
Ah!

03:19.830 --> 03:22.696
Mr. Gleason, when was your last drink?

03:22.743 --> 03:24.917
Two nights ago, which is why

03:24.942 --> 03:26.596
I need to get the hell out of here.

03:26.621 --> 03:28.234
Afraid I can't do that.

03:28.543 --> 03:30.428
Talk to this guy, will you please?

03:30.453 --> 03:31.934
I'm sorry, Chuck, the
doctor's in charge.

03:31.958 --> 03:33.570
No, I'm in charge, okay?

03:33.595 --> 03:34.971
I'm in charge. I know my rights.

03:34.996 --> 03:35.896
I don't have to stay here

03:35.921 --> 03:37.158
if I don't want to stay here.

03:37.182 --> 03:38.449
That's very true,

03:38.474 --> 03:39.707
but you're not going
to get far on that leg

03:39.732 --> 03:41.250
without ortho taking care of it.

03:41.275 --> 03:42.275
Okay, fine, man.

03:42.300 --> 03:43.039
It's cool.

03:43.064 --> 03:45.090
W-w-what are we talking about here,
two hours?

03:45.114 --> 03:46.825
Mr. Gleason,
you're going through delirium tremens.

03:46.850 --> 03:48.567
Your body is so used to
the presence of alcohol

03:48.592 --> 03:50.206
that it's reacting
violently to its absence.

03:50.231 --> 03:51.494
Blah, blah, blah!

03:51.519 --> 03:54.044
We need to keep you here a day
or so till you get through it.

03:54.069 --> 03:55.571
Ain't gonna happen, man.

03:55.706 --> 03:56.838
Okay?

03:56.982 --> 03:59.364
I seen what happens with the DTs.

03:59.389 --> 04:00.849
I can't go through that, please.

04:00.874 --> 04:03.024
We can't stop them,
but we have given you a sedative

04:03.049 --> 04:04.150
to make it easier.

04:04.175 --> 04:05.709
I'm sorry, but at this point,

04:05.734 --> 04:07.421
it's no longer safe for you to leave.

04:07.551 --> 04:09.550
[whimpers]

04:10.312 --> 04:12.474
[vomits]

04:12.499 --> 04:14.030
Okay.

04:14.423 --> 04:15.847
Okay.

04:15.872 --> 04:17.534
[retches]

04:18.952 --> 04:20.704
Hey, Maggie, can you call ortho

04:20.728 --> 04:21.862
and see what's taking so long?

04:21.887 --> 04:23.208
Sure can.

04:23.741 --> 04:25.041
Hey.

04:25.137 --> 04:27.097
Where's your wedding ring?

04:28.744 --> 04:29.802
I-I don't know.

04:29.827 --> 04:32.060
Um... I had it on when I got here.

04:32.085 --> 04:33.483
You didn't put it in your locker?

04:33.508 --> 04:34.953
No, I never take it off.

04:34.978 --> 04:36.030
Well, where else have you been?

04:36.054 --> 04:36.826
Re-trace your steps.

04:36.851 --> 04:38.681
I've been in and out of five rooms,
washing my hands.

04:38.706 --> 04:40.861
I mean, who knows how many
gloves I've taken on and off?

04:40.885 --> 04:42.580
<i>[tense music]</i>

04:43.166 --> 04:44.344
Maggie.

04:44.369 --> 04:46.404
All right, all right, I got this.

04:46.429 --> 04:48.796
Everyone, listen up.

04:48.821 --> 04:50.897
We're missing a gold wedding band,

04:50.923 --> 04:53.577
so take a room and
search every inch of it.

04:53.601 --> 04:55.593
From now on, nothing leaves the ED.

04:55.619 --> 04:58.477
Every sheet, every gown,
every piece of trash

04:58.502 --> 05:00.762
gets bagged and stored
until I search it.

05:00.787 --> 05:02.063
Got that?

05:02.088 --> 05:03.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:03.716 --> 05:06.825
Hey, we're gonna find it, okay?

05:06.850 --> 05:07.998
I'm gonna check in the lounge.

05:08.023 --> 05:09.056
- Okay.
- Thank you.

05:09.081 --> 05:09.955
Okay.

05:09.980 --> 05:11.550
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:12.607 --> 05:15.858
So this is Rose Wechsler, 83.

05:15.883 --> 05:18.185
Arrived from her nursing
facility confused and agitated.

05:18.210 --> 05:20.044
Ms. Wechsler, good morning.

05:20.069 --> 05:20.950
Baloney.

05:20.975 --> 05:22.487
Are you here for the sink?

05:22.511 --> 05:23.865
You know, I'm not.

05:23.890 --> 05:25.210
But it would help me out a great deal

05:25.235 --> 05:26.869
if you would tell me what year it was.

05:26.894 --> 05:29.223
Check your damn calendar.

05:29.248 --> 05:31.640
No wonder you people
never show up on time.

05:31.665 --> 05:32.698
That's completely my fault.

05:32.723 --> 05:34.130
Do you mind if I just shine...

05:34.155 --> 05:35.759
What are you, some kind of a maniac?

05:35.784 --> 05:37.150
Get the hell out of here!

05:37.175 --> 05:38.314
Thank you.

05:38.339 --> 05:39.439
Out!

05:39.464 --> 05:41.206
Lovely to meet you.

05:41.938 --> 05:43.184
What do you think?

05:43.209 --> 05:46.078
[sighs] Nursing home delirium.

05:46.103 --> 05:47.614
Acute cognitive dysfunction

05:47.638 --> 05:48.784
from some combination

05:48.809 --> 05:52.209
of dehydration, stasis, over-medication,

05:52.234 --> 05:53.834
and a lack of human engagement.

05:53.859 --> 05:55.112
Could be.

05:55.137 --> 05:58.006
She's neurologically intact but
her mucous membranes are dry.

05:58.031 --> 05:59.431
If you're right, fluids
will perk her up.

05:59.456 --> 06:00.740
Mm, yeah, for now.

06:00.878 --> 06:02.222
What?

06:03.379 --> 06:06.517
Well, I'm sorry,
it's just that her records indicate

06:06.541 --> 06:08.202
she led a remarkable life.

06:08.227 --> 06:10.861
Was one of the first female test pilots,
trained at NASA.

06:10.886 --> 06:11.946
Even if fluids work,

06:11.971 --> 06:14.640
it's sad seeing someone
like that wind up like this.

06:14.665 --> 06:15.312
Well...

06:15.337 --> 06:17.245
Incoming! Dr. Choi.

06:17.270 --> 06:18.470
We're going to Baghdad.

06:18.495 --> 06:20.206
- [alarm beeps]
- [indistinct P.A. announcement]

06:20.231 --> 06:21.441
On it.

06:21.730 --> 06:22.883
Talk to me.

06:22.908 --> 06:24.684
Frank McCormick. Here's his EKG.

06:24.709 --> 06:26.579
42, lost his rhythm again in the van.

06:26.604 --> 06:28.133
Shocked from v-fib in the field.

06:28.158 --> 06:29.258
Hang in there, Frank,
it's going to be okay.

06:29.283 --> 06:30.163
Excuse us, ma'am.

06:30.187 --> 06:31.208
Let's rotate.

06:31.233 --> 06:32.800
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

06:34.241 --> 06:37.217
All right, let's
transfer him on my count.

06:37.242 --> 06:39.219
One, two, three.

06:39.244 --> 06:40.089
Transfer.

06:40.114 --> 06:41.605
Dr. Choi, what have you got?

06:41.631 --> 06:43.111
STEMI. A big one.

06:43.136 --> 06:44.908
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:45.614 --> 06:46.859
[machines beeping]

06:46.884 --> 06:47.950
He flipped back into v-fib.

06:47.975 --> 06:49.585
- On it.
- STATs are dropping.

06:49.610 --> 06:51.136
- Frank.
- Paddles to Dr. Choi.

06:51.161 --> 06:52.442
Ma'am, ma'am, is this your husband?

06:52.467 --> 06:53.658
- Yes.
- He had a heart attack.

06:53.683 --> 06:54.403
Please step outside.

06:54.428 --> 06:55.740
- Oh, my God.
- Come with me

06:55.765 --> 06:56.919
and stand right there.

06:56.944 --> 06:58.599
- Charge 200.
- Charging.

06:58.624 --> 07:00.005
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:00.030 --> 07:01.881
- Clear.
- Clear.

07:01.906 --> 07:03.240
[machines beeping]

07:03.265 --> 07:04.476
[paddles shock]

07:04.502 --> 07:06.674
[machine flat-lining]

07:06.699 --> 07:08.320
Charging.

07:08.345 --> 07:10.878
[paddles whirring]

07:10.903 --> 07:12.525
Clear.

07:13.421 --> 07:15.025
[paddles shock]

07:15.050 --> 07:16.317
[machine beeping]

07:16.342 --> 07:18.276
Heart rate's back to 65.

07:18.301 --> 07:19.756
Pressure's 115 over 60.

07:19.781 --> 07:21.233
All right, let's get
him up to the cath lab.

07:21.258 --> 07:23.830
Based on his EKG, he's
gonna need a bypass.

07:23.855 --> 07:25.217
Okay, let's go.

07:25.243 --> 07:26.605
Watch the lines.

07:26.630 --> 07:28.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:30.260 --> 07:31.526
Wait.

07:31.551 --> 07:33.543
Did you say he needs
a bypass? Yes, ma'am.

07:33.568 --> 07:34.548
We got your husband's rhythm back,

07:34.573 --> 07:35.868
but he's still not out of the woods.

07:35.893 --> 07:38.367
We need to find the blockage
that caused his heart attack

07:38.392 --> 07:39.237
and most likely,

07:39.262 --> 07:41.264
we will graft new vessels on around it.

07:41.289 --> 07:43.256
But that means going on a
heart-lung machine, right?

07:43.281 --> 07:44.056
Yes, it does.

07:44.081 --> 07:45.452
Then I'll have to refuse.

07:45.909 --> 07:47.270
Refuse? What?

07:47.295 --> 07:48.961
My husband can't have any surgery

07:48.986 --> 07:50.566
that involves the
administration of blood.

07:50.591 --> 07:52.115
We're Jehovah's Witnesses.

07:52.140 --> 07:54.499
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:54.524 --> 07:56.064
Stop!

07:56.089 --> 07:57.790
Stop it! Get it off of me.

07:57.815 --> 07:59.444
They're inside of this thing now.

07:59.469 --> 08:01.706
Chuck, you're hallucinating again.

08:01.731 --> 08:03.231
It's part of the DTs.

08:03.256 --> 08:05.189
We're gonna increase your sedatives.

08:05.214 --> 08:07.009
I don't want a sedative.

08:07.034 --> 08:08.309
How many times do I
got to tell you that?

08:08.334 --> 08:10.869
I don't need a sedative.
I don't need a sedative.

08:10.894 --> 08:12.027
I need a drink.

08:12.052 --> 08:13.549
You know I can't do that.

08:13.575 --> 08:16.405
Then get the hell out of here!

08:19.607 --> 08:21.609
Hey, how long have I known you?

08:21.634 --> 08:22.494
Years.

08:22.519 --> 08:25.082
Every time you come in
here, you are sicker.

08:25.107 --> 08:26.887
One of these times you're
going to be too far gone.

08:26.912 --> 08:28.033
Chuck, listen to me.

08:28.058 --> 08:30.684
You're never gonna beat
this if you give in now.

08:30.948 --> 08:33.811
[crying] I'm never gonna beat this.

08:36.279 --> 08:38.542
I ain't beating nothing.

08:40.441 --> 08:42.341
Please help. Make it stop.

08:42.366 --> 08:43.767
Please, please, make it stop.

08:43.792 --> 08:45.935
I'm trying to help you.

08:47.833 --> 08:49.967
[vomits]

08:50.242 --> 08:52.128
[clears throat]

08:52.153 --> 08:54.944
[gags]

08:55.795 --> 08:59.496
I told you... I told
you how to help me,

08:59.747 --> 09:01.740
but you don't listen.

09:01.765 --> 09:03.589
Going to increase your sedatives,

09:03.614 --> 09:06.022
and I'm going to get
you a clean blanket.

09:06.896 --> 09:09.510
I don't need a clean blanket.

09:10.070 --> 09:12.546
I need a drink.

09:13.056 --> 09:16.058
Youse are killing me with all your help!

09:16.678 --> 09:20.711
<i>[dark music]</i>

09:24.512 --> 09:26.585
Frank, we respect your beliefs, we do.

09:26.610 --> 09:29.246
But the fact is, you're going
to have another heart attack.

09:29.271 --> 09:31.145
The only question is when.

09:31.170 --> 09:32.503
You page me?

09:32.770 --> 09:36.396
This is Dr. Downey,
our top cardiothoracic surgeon.

09:36.421 --> 09:37.940
I was just explaining to the McCormicks

09:37.965 --> 09:39.432
that unfortunately surgery

09:39.457 --> 09:41.051
is the only option that we have left.

09:41.076 --> 09:43.436
And I was explaining that
we need an alternative

09:43.461 --> 09:45.323
that doesn't involve the
administration of blood.

09:45.349 --> 09:47.389
It is his own blood.

09:47.414 --> 09:48.698
It's re-circulated.

09:48.723 --> 09:50.117
Blood contains the gift of life.

09:50.143 --> 09:52.236
Once it leaves the body,
it's contaminated forever.

09:52.261 --> 09:54.056
I know you think we're being difficult,

09:54.081 --> 09:56.299
but this isn't just about the danger

09:56.324 --> 09:58.219
that Frank's body is in right now.

09:58.244 --> 10:01.180
It's about he and I being able
to spend eternity together.

10:01.205 --> 10:03.138
We understand, but you have to...

10:03.163 --> 10:04.886
What about bloodless surgery?

10:05.288 --> 10:06.567
What's that?

10:06.659 --> 10:08.561
It's where we do it off-pump.

10:08.658 --> 10:10.832
Operate on the heart
while it's still beating.

10:10.885 --> 10:12.887
<i>[tense music]</i>

10:12.912 --> 10:14.412
You can do that?

10:14.437 --> 10:15.538
Yes.

10:15.563 --> 10:18.294
Though it comes with significant risks.

10:18.319 --> 10:21.788
For the McCormicks,
the heart-lung machine is a risk.

10:21.813 --> 10:24.647
Stopping the heart,
removing the blood to oxygenate it,

10:24.672 --> 10:27.488
then putting it back
violates their faith,

10:28.100 --> 10:30.061
so let's do it without the machine.

10:30.086 --> 10:32.277
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:32.671 --> 10:34.673
Excuse us for a moment.

10:35.016 --> 10:38.437
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:43.011 --> 10:44.576
He's got bad three vessel disease.

10:44.601 --> 10:46.333
He's a terrible candidate.

10:46.358 --> 10:47.859
It's too high of a risk.

10:47.884 --> 10:49.348
Higher than not doing anything at all?

10:49.373 --> 10:51.103
Let's at least give them some time

10:51.128 --> 10:53.888
to see if they want to
choose the safer option.

10:53.913 --> 10:55.247
We don't want to wait.

10:55.272 --> 10:56.805
We want to do the bloodless surgery.

10:56.830 --> 10:58.394
Okay.

10:58.419 --> 11:00.479
I'll inform the OR.

11:00.620 --> 11:02.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:05.786 --> 11:07.385
Please, it's a lot...

11:07.410 --> 11:08.936
Please.

11:10.901 --> 11:12.532
You need to up his benzos.

11:12.557 --> 11:14.772
I already did, twice.

11:14.796 --> 11:16.931
Then give him a
milligram of Haldol, too.

11:16.956 --> 11:18.273
[sighs]

11:18.299 --> 11:20.236
I'll tell you, when I
was a clinical nurse

11:20.261 --> 11:22.445
I used to dread DT patients.

11:22.470 --> 11:24.003
I know, such misery.

11:24.028 --> 11:26.110
And most of the time
they're back in two months

11:26.135 --> 11:27.581
to do it all over again.

11:27.606 --> 11:28.806
Mm-hmm.

11:28.927 --> 11:31.200
I lost my wedding ring recently,

11:31.225 --> 11:33.060
didn't find it for three days.

11:33.085 --> 11:34.199
What did Bert say?

11:34.224 --> 11:35.781
You know, he didn't say anything,

11:35.806 --> 11:39.148
which was weird because
he's usually so observant.

11:39.173 --> 11:39.946
Huh.

11:39.971 --> 11:42.172
Oh, excuse me. Daniel.

11:42.197 --> 11:43.654
What are you doing tonight?

11:43.679 --> 11:45.179
Mm, working, why?

11:45.204 --> 11:47.673
Well, an old friend of Bert's and mine

11:47.698 --> 11:48.697
has moved to town

11:48.722 --> 11:50.590
and I thought we could all go to dinner.

11:50.615 --> 11:53.545
You know, sounds like a blast
but I really am slammed.

11:53.858 --> 11:54.993
Come on, Daniel.

11:55.018 --> 11:56.953
Bert's been so grumpy lately,

11:56.978 --> 11:59.496
and he always cheers up
when he talks to you.

11:59.521 --> 12:00.364
What's going on?

12:00.389 --> 12:03.400
It's a long story,
but you'd really be helping me out.

12:03.425 --> 12:08.271
Besides, Maribel loves
Scotch and ballroom dancing.

12:08.296 --> 12:10.110
You haven't been out in a while.

12:10.135 --> 12:11.334
You know, there's a reason for that.

12:11.359 --> 12:12.494
There's this new study out,

12:12.519 --> 12:13.960
says dating can lead to marriage.

12:13.985 --> 12:16.127
It's just a friendly dinner.

12:16.152 --> 12:18.309
Yeah, and I'm still paying
two and a half alimonies.

12:18.334 --> 12:20.087
Those friendly dinners
can get expensive.

12:20.112 --> 12:22.773
Ooh, Ms. Reese,
any word on that nursing home patient?

12:22.797 --> 12:23.570
Actually, there is.

12:23.595 --> 12:24.867
- Daniel.
- I got to go.

12:24.892 --> 12:26.009
Thank you so much for the invite.

12:26.034 --> 12:26.632
Best to Bert.

12:26.657 --> 12:28.041
We'll do it next time.

12:28.262 --> 12:31.028
So the good news is,
Ms. Wechsler's doing much better

12:31.053 --> 12:31.997
after some fluids.

12:32.023 --> 12:33.056
She's awake and alert.

12:33.081 --> 12:33.926
That is good news.

12:33.951 --> 12:35.848
Yes, though she does still have a fever

12:35.873 --> 12:37.706
and is reporting lower abdominal pain.

12:37.731 --> 12:38.714
Fluids and scans?

12:38.738 --> 12:40.881
All negative except for a
slightly elevated white count,

12:40.907 --> 12:43.242
but I'm already doing an
infectious workup now.

12:43.267 --> 12:44.530
Sounds like a great plan.

12:44.554 --> 12:45.788
What's the bad news?

12:45.876 --> 12:48.166
This is Wanda Stern.

12:52.195 --> 12:53.961
In from the same nursing home.

12:53.986 --> 12:55.235
She has a 101 fever

12:55.260 --> 12:56.952
and feels Nixon is just

12:56.977 --> 12:59.691
what this country needs
to run out the commies.

13:00.718 --> 13:02.202
Fluids and labs?

13:02.227 --> 13:04.085
Fluids and labs.

13:08.328 --> 13:10.162
Hey.

13:10.266 --> 13:11.825
Sorry about your ring.

13:11.850 --> 13:13.116
It's so stupid.

13:13.141 --> 13:14.471
I can't believe I lost it.

13:14.496 --> 13:15.462
No, no, no. Come on.

13:15.487 --> 13:17.055
These things, they happen.

13:17.080 --> 13:19.191
No, illnesses happen.

13:19.216 --> 13:20.462
Bad weather happens.

13:20.487 --> 13:22.689
This is on me.

13:24.153 --> 13:28.016
Look, I'm on all your patients,
so don't worry, okay?

13:28.041 --> 13:31.578
Just... try to take it easy.

13:33.004 --> 13:35.522
I feel so terrible.

13:35.547 --> 13:40.086
Like, like I betrayed Jeff,
like I didn't care enough.

13:46.356 --> 13:48.224
Hey, April?

13:48.249 --> 13:50.205
April.

13:50.440 --> 13:51.526
What's in the bag?

13:51.551 --> 13:53.893
Nothing, it's a personal item.

13:54.027 --> 13:56.007
Is that a bottle of booze?

13:56.386 --> 13:57.989
[sighs]

13:58.014 --> 13:59.820
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

14:00.659 --> 14:02.410
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:04.741 --> 14:06.823
You were going to give
that to Mr. Gleason?

14:06.848 --> 14:08.479
My nursing supervisor
did it all the time.

14:08.504 --> 14:10.344
April, it's against protocol.

14:10.369 --> 14:12.678
Since when do you care about that?

14:12.856 --> 14:15.178
I care about getting our
patient through this.

14:15.203 --> 14:17.455
Does he look like he's
getting through this?

14:17.480 --> 14:18.682
He needs a drink.

14:18.707 --> 14:20.808
I didn't say it would be easy, but that?

14:20.833 --> 14:21.949
That's just a Band-Aid.

14:21.974 --> 14:24.680
I come in here every day and
I put Band-Aids on patients

14:24.705 --> 14:26.180
and most of them thank me for it.

14:26.205 --> 14:28.614
And he may thank you,
but you're not helping him.

14:28.639 --> 14:30.138
And you are?

14:30.162 --> 14:32.298
Standing around while
he dies in front of us?

14:32.323 --> 14:34.437
This man has a chance
to get past his problem

14:34.462 --> 14:35.427
and make a new start.

14:35.452 --> 14:37.119
He's telling us that
he doesn't want that,

14:37.144 --> 14:38.301
and it's up to us to listen.

14:38.326 --> 14:39.158
No, no, no, no.

14:39.183 --> 14:40.242
It's not my job to listen.

14:40.267 --> 14:41.769
I'm a doctor.

14:41.794 --> 14:44.194
It's my job to decide
what is best for him.

14:44.219 --> 14:47.028
That is exactly why I'm a nurse.

14:47.053 --> 14:50.974
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:56.145 --> 14:57.346
Hey.

14:57.371 --> 14:59.479
Uh, Frank McCormick
is going into surgery.

14:59.504 --> 15:02.338
I need you to load his
angio into the system.

15:04.795 --> 15:05.917
You doctor Rhodes?

15:05.942 --> 15:07.477
Uh, yep.

15:08.924 --> 15:11.000
Should be up now.

15:11.446 --> 15:12.785
<i>[tense music]</i>

15:13.544 --> 15:16.075
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:16.910 --> 15:19.830
_

15:20.132 --> 15:22.132
Yeah, thanks.

15:22.863 --> 15:26.724
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:30.610 --> 15:32.684
No luck yet, huh?

15:32.709 --> 15:35.562
Not yet, but we haven't
even gone through the trash.

15:35.780 --> 15:37.280
Are you okay?

15:37.305 --> 15:38.573
Yeah, uh...

15:38.598 --> 15:41.690
[clears throat] My head is... spinning.

15:41.715 --> 15:45.687
I feel like I'm gonna throw up, but...
oh, Maggie.

15:45.712 --> 15:47.677
Natalie, I'm gonna find your ring,

15:47.702 --> 15:48.702
but in the meantime,

15:48.727 --> 15:49.954
I want you to go in there,

15:49.979 --> 15:50.978
have a drink of water,

15:51.003 --> 15:51.966
and lie down.

15:51.991 --> 15:52.836
Okay? Mmhmm.

15:52.861 --> 15:54.897
All right.

15:58.263 --> 15:59.663
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:59.981 --> 16:01.196
Natalie?

16:01.221 --> 16:02.756
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:07.251 --> 16:10.060
I don't know why you guys
are ordering all these tests.

16:10.489 --> 16:12.576
I'm anemic. It was nothing.

16:12.601 --> 16:14.457
That's not what the EKG's saying.

16:14.482 --> 16:15.967
I'm seeing elevated ST segments

16:15.992 --> 16:17.523
in the anterior and lateral leads.

16:17.548 --> 16:19.048
Where?

16:19.320 --> 16:20.555
Tell echo we're bringing her upstairs.

16:20.580 --> 16:21.143
Echo?

16:21.168 --> 16:23.427
I have no cardiac
history, no risk factors.

16:23.452 --> 16:25.920
You guys are just being overly
cautious because it's me.

16:25.945 --> 16:27.956
Nat, that's darn right
that's what we're doing.

16:27.981 --> 16:30.324
Stop being stubborn and
listen to the man, please?

16:30.349 --> 16:31.385
Let's go.

16:31.410 --> 16:33.467
Ugh.

16:34.554 --> 16:38.977
On Wednesdays,
I go downstairs to the beauty shop.

16:39.002 --> 16:41.602
My neighbor Sheila always does my hair.

16:41.743 --> 16:43.076
Okay.

16:43.101 --> 16:44.195
How about the card room?

16:44.220 --> 16:45.454
I play a lot of canasta.

16:45.479 --> 16:47.948
- In the south lobby?
- No, darling.

16:47.973 --> 16:49.573
Uh, in the north.

16:49.598 --> 16:50.959
Oh.

16:50.984 --> 16:52.245
How we doing, ladies?

16:52.271 --> 16:53.271
Any luck?

16:53.296 --> 16:54.663
Wanda here is lovely,

16:54.688 --> 16:57.361
and though I appreciate your
theory that our conditions

16:57.386 --> 16:59.724
may arise from the same source,

16:59.929 --> 17:03.288
I'm afraid the only thing we
have in common is Sinai Gardens.

17:03.313 --> 17:04.848
Ah.

17:05.387 --> 17:07.054
Ms. Reese, could I, um...

17:07.079 --> 17:08.146
could I talk to you for a moment?

17:08.164 --> 17:08.876
Mm-hmm.

17:08.901 --> 17:10.935
Keep at it.

17:12.749 --> 17:14.357
[sighs]

17:14.382 --> 17:15.646
Their labs are all negative,

17:15.671 --> 17:17.573
but both are febrile with leukocytosis,

17:17.598 --> 17:19.250
and infections in the elderly

17:19.275 --> 17:21.680
can present quite
differently than normal.

17:21.704 --> 17:23.941
I think we need to start
looking for zebras.

17:23.964 --> 17:26.391
Rickettsia, leptospirosis...

17:26.415 --> 17:28.840
Ms. Stern had some
redness in her left eye.

17:28.865 --> 17:29.623
You notice that?

17:29.648 --> 17:31.349
Probably from the chlorine in the pool.

17:31.374 --> 17:33.072
She likes to do water aerobics.

17:33.097 --> 17:34.567
But consider the symptoms.

17:34.593 --> 17:37.327
Acute delirium, severe dehydration,

17:37.352 --> 17:41.474
lower abdominal pain, one itchy red eye.

17:41.565 --> 17:43.425
Like I said, in an 85-year-old,

17:43.450 --> 17:44.437
it could be anything.

17:44.462 --> 17:45.885
If these women were
closer to you in age,

17:45.909 --> 17:47.946
what might you suspect?

17:49.662 --> 17:51.663
[gasps]

17:51.688 --> 17:54.090
<i>[tense music]</i>

17:54.115 --> 17:55.448
No.

17:55.473 --> 17:56.887
No, no, no, no, no.

17:56.912 --> 17:57.912
Why not?

17:57.937 --> 17:59.862
No. Because they're old ladies.

17:59.887 --> 18:01.092
They can't have gonorrhea.

18:01.117 --> 18:03.234
Are you trying to tell me
that because they're old,

18:03.260 --> 18:05.015
they can no longer be sexually active?

18:05.040 --> 18:07.573
Well, come on, they barely have
the energy to play canasta,

18:07.598 --> 18:08.640
whatever that is.

18:08.665 --> 18:09.797
I say we keep digging.

18:09.823 --> 18:11.720
Ahem. There's a gentleman

18:11.745 --> 18:13.513
from the retirement home out there

18:13.538 --> 18:15.640
inquiring about the status
of your two patients.

18:16.707 --> 18:19.153
Says his name is Clyde.

18:19.178 --> 18:21.727
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:21.867 --> 18:23.354
Hmm.

18:23.380 --> 18:27.527
Maybe they, um,
have something in common after all.

18:27.761 --> 18:30.358
We're gonna need some swabs.

18:30.383 --> 18:32.153
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:34.286 --> 18:35.969
Dr. Halstead!

18:35.994 --> 18:37.206
What happened?

18:37.231 --> 18:38.575
He just started vomiting blood.

18:38.954 --> 18:41.780
Must have ruptured an esophageal varix.

18:41.805 --> 18:43.793
Prep a Minnesota tube and call for MTP.

18:43.818 --> 18:45.121
I need to intubate.

18:45.146 --> 18:46.436
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

18:46.461 --> 18:48.977
It's from years of alcoholic cirrhosis.

18:49.002 --> 18:51.036
The vessels get dilated and tortured.

18:51.061 --> 18:52.718
But why's this all happening right now?

18:52.743 --> 18:54.981
Must have ruptured
from all the vomiting.

18:55.006 --> 18:57.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:02.181 --> 19:04.182
Right, tube.

19:04.207 --> 19:06.322
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:09.727 --> 19:11.030
Got an airway.

19:11.055 --> 19:12.158
Bag him.

19:12.182 --> 19:14.081
Good breath sounds bilaterally.

19:14.106 --> 19:14.975
We need to stop this bleeding.

19:15.000 --> 19:16.810
- Minnesota tube.
- Yes, Doctor.

19:16.835 --> 19:18.570
- What do you need?
- Start a groin line.

19:18.595 --> 19:21.245
Get a rapid transfuser,
and give him two of blood, stat.

19:21.270 --> 19:22.355
I need more suction.

19:22.380 --> 19:23.393
I got it.

19:23.418 --> 19:25.374
Send a runner to
Central for the infuser,

19:25.398 --> 19:26.652
and call the blood bank.

19:26.677 --> 19:28.372
I'm on it.

19:28.397 --> 19:30.734
I can't see a damn thing.

19:30.759 --> 19:33.132
All right, I'm gonna
have to go in blind.

19:33.157 --> 19:34.622
Line's in.

19:34.647 --> 19:36.436
Start the MTP.

19:36.875 --> 19:38.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:38.333 --> 19:40.266
Pressure's down to 80 over 40.

19:40.291 --> 19:41.455
He's bleeding out.

19:41.480 --> 19:43.021
Come on.

19:43.389 --> 19:45.657
Come on.

19:45.682 --> 19:47.472
Got it!

19:47.497 --> 19:49.398
- Blood's going.
- Good.

19:49.423 --> 19:50.843
Ready to inflate the internal balloons.

19:50.868 --> 19:51.607
Syringe.

19:51.632 --> 19:52.832
Want an X-ray for placement?

19:52.857 --> 19:53.525
No time.

19:53.550 --> 19:54.924
As soon as the balloons are inflated,

19:54.949 --> 19:56.692
we'll know whether the pressure
they're placing on the vessels

19:56.717 --> 19:58.493
is enough to staunch the bleeding.

19:58.518 --> 20:00.648
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:03.035 --> 20:04.169
Bleeding's stopped.

20:04.194 --> 20:06.036
For now.

20:06.472 --> 20:08.795
<i>[tense music]</i>

20:09.840 --> 20:11.996
Call GI to cauterize the vessels.

20:12.021 --> 20:13.222
Okay.

20:13.247 --> 20:16.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:18.171 --> 20:20.239
I'm doing everything I can.

20:20.316 --> 20:24.091
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:24.945 --> 20:26.448
Dr. Halstead?

20:26.473 --> 20:29.679
Dr. Manning's results from echo.

20:31.000 --> 20:37.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

20:38.227 --> 20:40.263
Knock, knock.

20:41.883 --> 20:44.359
Hey.

20:45.560 --> 20:47.186
Did you get my echo results?

20:47.212 --> 20:49.302
Yeah, good news.

20:49.327 --> 20:51.428
You definitely did not
have a heart attack.

20:51.783 --> 20:52.783
You see?

20:52.808 --> 20:54.209
That's what I've been saying.

20:54.234 --> 20:56.092
But you did have a cardiac event.

20:56.491 --> 20:59.959
Uh, takotsubo cardiomyopathy.

20:59.984 --> 21:01.911
Let me see that.

21:03.096 --> 21:06.619
Um, spasm on your coronary artery.

21:06.644 --> 21:11.182
Would explain the shortness
of breath and chest pain.

21:12.081 --> 21:15.015
Scary for sure, but
completely reversible.

21:15.040 --> 21:18.078
Yeah, we should have you
out of here in a day or two.

21:20.256 --> 21:23.142
Losing my wedding ring.

21:23.830 --> 21:25.489
That's what triggered this.

21:25.514 --> 21:27.541
Hey, it's not always easy
to pinpoint the cause

21:27.566 --> 21:30.229
of the stress. You...
you just can't know.

21:30.254 --> 21:33.149
Will, no, you don't
have to sugar-coat it.

21:33.174 --> 21:35.329
I know the colloquial term for this.

21:35.354 --> 21:37.234
Broken heart syndrome.

21:37.259 --> 21:39.846
<i>[solemn music]</i>

21:40.174 --> 21:42.975
This is about, uh...

21:43.000 --> 21:45.201
This is about Jeff.

21:45.648 --> 21:49.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:52.211 --> 21:55.113
Chance of another episode
is incredibly low.

21:55.138 --> 21:57.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:57.597 --> 21:59.865
You will get past this,

21:59.890 --> 22:02.150
I promise.

22:02.953 --> 22:08.718
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:09.948 --> 22:11.949
Yeah.

22:12.776 --> 22:17.667
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:18.562 --> 22:20.593
I came as soon as Maggie called me.

22:20.618 --> 22:21.374
How is she?

22:21.399 --> 22:24.310
Hi, uh...  she's gonna be okay.

22:24.335 --> 22:25.897
Oh.

22:26.686 --> 22:27.941
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:28.801 --> 22:31.838
Hi.

22:40.294 --> 22:43.172
And LAD is finished.

22:43.860 --> 22:50.590
Raising the heart ventrally
to get at the RCA.

22:53.913 --> 22:55.742
Uh-huh.

22:56.526 --> 22:59.114
Two-thirds of the way there.

22:59.303 --> 23:01.273
This is the big one.

23:01.725 --> 23:02.700
Right there.

23:02.725 --> 23:04.031
Scalpel and Gerald.

23:04.056 --> 23:05.056
Scalpel.

23:05.081 --> 23:05.902
[machines beeping]

23:05.927 --> 23:07.026
Blood pressure bottomed out.

23:07.051 --> 23:08.016
You got to lower the heart back down.

23:08.041 --> 23:09.559
Okay.

23:09.584 --> 23:11.761
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

23:12.387 --> 23:13.919
Okay.

23:13.944 --> 23:15.184
Marty?

23:15.209 --> 23:16.991
It's not coming back.

23:17.016 --> 23:18.818
He's in v-fib.

23:18.843 --> 23:20.357
We got to put him on the pump.

23:20.382 --> 23:24.785
No, we'll defibrillate him,
continue as planned.

23:24.811 --> 23:25.810
And then what?

23:25.835 --> 23:28.317
This is gonna happen again.

23:28.697 --> 23:30.312
- Clear.
- Clear.

23:30.337 --> 23:31.872
[instrument whirring]

23:31.897 --> 23:33.364
[machine beeping]

23:33.389 --> 23:35.034
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:35.681 --> 23:37.782
Still v-fib.

23:37.807 --> 23:39.411
We have to put him on the pump.

23:39.436 --> 23:40.670
We don't have a choice.

23:40.695 --> 23:41.928
Charge to 50.

23:41.953 --> 23:42.792
Charging.

23:42.817 --> 23:44.685
[instrument whirring]

23:44.710 --> 23:45.844
Clear.

23:45.869 --> 23:48.477
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:50.529 --> 23:52.423
This isn't working.

23:52.456 --> 23:55.944
We need to get the perfusionist
and the bypass team in here now.

23:55.969 --> 23:57.130
That's not an option, Dr. Rhodes.

23:57.155 --> 23:58.623
Then we will get his wife in here

23:58.648 --> 24:00.487
and we will get her consent.

24:00.512 --> 24:04.500
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:06.725 --> 24:09.455
It's his ball game.

24:10.553 --> 24:16.197
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:23.177 --> 24:26.012
I don't understand. Is Frank okay?

24:26.155 --> 24:28.577
Please, put this on.

24:28.602 --> 24:31.210
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:31.235 --> 24:33.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:35.411 --> 24:37.887
We're not getting the pressure back.

24:37.912 --> 24:39.724
Frank, oh, my God.

24:39.749 --> 24:41.289
Your husband is dying.

24:41.314 --> 24:43.852
I'm pumping his heart with my hands.

24:43.877 --> 24:45.979
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:47.565 --> 24:49.683
Mrs. McCormick.

24:50.996 --> 24:53.687
If you don't authorize this right now,

24:53.767 --> 24:55.992
you'll never see him alive again.

24:56.101 --> 25:02.089
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:07.817 --> 25:10.489
Is there really no other way?

25:11.614 --> 25:13.448
No.

25:13.981 --> 25:17.035
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:17.396 --> 25:20.593
Do what you have to.

25:22.799 --> 25:25.481
Forgive me, Jehovah.

25:25.565 --> 25:27.899
Why don't you come with me outside?

25:28.337 --> 25:30.796
Right, let's hook him
up and get to work.

25:31.151 --> 25:32.778
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:33.792 --> 25:36.292
This is the right thing to do.

25:36.436 --> 25:41.095
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:41.230 --> 25:42.508
Thank you.

25:42.533 --> 25:45.674
Yeah. That was Julia.

25:45.699 --> 25:47.344
She needs me to relieve her.

25:47.369 --> 25:51.073
I could bring Owen back
here a little later.

25:51.098 --> 25:52.615
Maybe later tonight.

25:53.624 --> 25:56.668
Okay, all right, well, you just, uh...

25:56.694 --> 26:00.899
you just call me and... and let me
know what you'd like, all right?

26:02.162 --> 26:03.892
Oh, uh, Helen, actually,

26:03.917 --> 26:04.683
I'm sorry.

26:04.708 --> 26:06.342
One last thing. Mmhmm.

26:06.514 --> 26:08.630
Do you know where Jeff got my ring?

26:08.737 --> 26:12.652
Well, not right offhand,
but I-I could look that up.

26:12.677 --> 26:14.180
Please.

26:15.699 --> 26:18.631
You're not thinking about
replacing the ring, are you?

26:18.666 --> 26:20.702
Yes, I am.

26:23.608 --> 26:25.919
Do you really think that's a good idea?

26:26.223 --> 26:27.857
Why wouldn't it be?

26:28.120 --> 26:31.593
Natalie, I know you loved Jeff.

26:31.618 --> 26:32.553
Jeff loved you,

26:32.578 --> 26:35.911
but maybe losing the ring is a sign.

26:35.936 --> 26:36.989
A sign?

26:37.014 --> 26:38.390
Natalie...

26:39.908 --> 26:42.243
what do they call this?

26:42.268 --> 26:44.402
Broken heart syndrome.

26:44.427 --> 26:46.168
<i>[solemn music]</i>

26:46.207 --> 26:48.729
Your grieving is so great

26:48.803 --> 26:51.039
that it has put you in a hospital bed

26:51.064 --> 26:54.163
and is keeping you from
coming home to see your son.

26:54.318 --> 26:57.565
So, maybe you just...

26:58.267 --> 27:00.569
you need to let go a little bit.

27:00.594 --> 27:02.028
How could you say that?

27:02.053 --> 27:03.887
I would never let go of Jeff.

27:03.912 --> 27:06.484
I don't mean let go of him.

27:06.509 --> 27:07.642
Just...

27:09.726 --> 27:11.860
move forward.

27:11.996 --> 27:14.299
[sobs]

27:15.261 --> 27:17.446
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:18.596 --> 27:20.598
You just...

27:20.685 --> 27:22.403
you call me and let me know

27:22.428 --> 27:24.848
if you need anything from home.

27:25.566 --> 27:28.410
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:32.565 --> 27:34.199
The clap?

27:34.224 --> 27:35.748
Yikes.

27:35.773 --> 27:38.115
Have Rose and Wanda been told?

27:38.790 --> 27:40.292
How did they take it?

27:40.317 --> 27:42.050
You'd have to ask them.

27:42.075 --> 27:43.409
Mr. Glickman,

27:43.434 --> 27:45.326
partner notification
is an important part

27:45.351 --> 27:46.485
of gonorrhea treatment,

27:46.510 --> 27:48.463
and while we really don't
want to be intrusive...

27:48.488 --> 27:50.417
A gentleman never tells.

27:50.546 --> 27:53.527
But if there are others,
they should be informed.

27:55.288 --> 27:57.222
There's Cookie.

27:57.642 --> 27:59.241
Beautiful blue eyes.

27:59.266 --> 28:00.575
Cookie?

28:00.600 --> 28:03.439
Sylvia, marvelous sense of humor.

28:03.464 --> 28:04.980
So you're sleeping with
four different women?

28:05.005 --> 28:06.157
Ms. Reese.

28:06.182 --> 28:09.461
You make it sound tawdry.

28:09.787 --> 28:11.455
It's not like that.

28:11.480 --> 28:14.229
At our age, there are very few men left,

28:14.254 --> 28:16.966
and people need companionship.

28:17.062 --> 28:19.897
I make them happy, they make me happy.

28:20.286 --> 28:22.912
And I love them, all of them.

28:23.468 --> 28:25.162
All of them.

28:25.225 --> 28:29.004
I think of it as assisted loving.

28:29.873 --> 28:33.678
We'll get you a shot of
ceftriaxone and azithromycin.

28:33.703 --> 28:36.740
The nurse will be with you shortly.

28:41.756 --> 28:43.584
Don't touch that. Get away.

28:43.609 --> 28:44.755
Hey, Dr. Choi.

28:44.780 --> 28:46.363
Earl said to give this back to you.

28:46.388 --> 28:47.499
What... what do you mean?

28:47.524 --> 28:49.367
Made such a racket,
wouldn't let him get any sleep.

28:49.392 --> 28:50.599
Said he's going to get a gerbil.

28:50.624 --> 28:52.403
Don't touch that. Get away, get away.

28:52.428 --> 28:53.739
Sorry, Maggie, I got to go.

28:53.764 --> 28:55.396
Hey, what am I supposed to do with it?

28:55.421 --> 28:56.085
I don't know.

28:56.110 --> 28:57.523
Put him in the doctors' lounge.

28:57.550 --> 28:59.499
- [scoffs]
- Get away, get away.

28:59.524 --> 29:01.066
Come on.

29:01.784 --> 29:04.820
[indistinct P.A. announcement]

29:28.323 --> 29:30.391
[laughs softly]

29:31.384 --> 29:33.235
Hm.

29:33.260 --> 29:35.937
Oh, Frank, I was so scared.

29:36.077 --> 29:38.316
Told you it'd be all right.

29:38.476 --> 29:40.578
Jehovah lit the path.

29:41.048 --> 29:43.440
It was His will.

29:44.382 --> 29:46.850
These doctors,

29:47.010 --> 29:50.047
maybe you should do
every surgery this way.

29:54.256 --> 29:55.825
[chuckles softly]

29:58.953 --> 30:02.486
Mr. McCormick, you should know

30:02.511 --> 30:05.877
that there were complications
with the surgery.

30:06.291 --> 30:08.892
What kind of complications?

30:09.242 --> 30:13.055
We had to use the bypass
machine after all.

30:13.080 --> 30:16.146
I thought we made our wishes clear.

30:16.824 --> 30:18.950
Did they tell you they were doing this?

30:18.983 --> 30:19.920
They did.

30:19.945 --> 30:22.213
And you gave them your permission?

30:22.620 --> 30:24.461
<i>[tense music]</i>

30:25.275 --> 30:27.634
How could you do this to me?

30:27.720 --> 30:30.808
I did it for you. For us.

30:30.833 --> 30:32.913
You weren't going to
survive the surgery.

30:32.938 --> 30:35.648
And now how am I supposed
to survive eternity?

30:35.673 --> 30:37.307
Frank, I'm sorry.

30:37.332 --> 30:39.421
- Get out.
- Please.

30:39.446 --> 30:40.751
Get out.

30:41.606 --> 30:43.272
[cries]

30:44.138 --> 30:47.576
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:47.603 --> 30:50.605
You had no right.

30:51.986 --> 30:54.127
You had no right.

30:55.260 --> 30:59.747
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:10.803 --> 31:14.461
That is why we don't disregard patients'
wishes.

31:14.486 --> 31:17.487
Have you read the fine print
of what they believe in?

31:17.512 --> 31:20.581
They can accept all
the fractions of blood

31:20.606 --> 31:22.313
but they can't accept them all together.

31:22.338 --> 31:24.029
Does that make any sense to you?

31:24.054 --> 31:25.524
Doesn't have to make sense to us.

31:25.549 --> 31:28.121
If he believed he would live longer

31:28.147 --> 31:29.921
if his wounds were
dressed in green bandages,

31:29.946 --> 31:31.370
then we give him green bandages.

31:31.396 --> 31:33.965
Not if the green bandages
are going to kill him.

31:33.990 --> 31:35.701
Yeah, even if it kills him.

31:36.449 --> 31:40.619
David, do you really believe that?

31:40.644 --> 31:42.846
Or is this just because this is the day

31:42.871 --> 31:45.492
that your liver is going to be ablated?

31:45.826 --> 31:48.173
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:48.598 --> 31:52.602
I saw your name on the board in IR.

31:52.928 --> 31:54.943
The mass on my liver isn't shrinking.

31:54.968 --> 31:56.625
We're going to try and reduce it again.

31:56.650 --> 31:58.517
In fact, I should mosey down there.

31:58.542 --> 32:01.296
You're a good surgeon, Dr. Rhodes,

32:01.679 --> 32:03.586
but saving a life isn't
always the answer,

32:03.611 --> 32:06.007
and you will never be a great surgeon

32:06.207 --> 32:08.864
until you understand that.

32:10.218 --> 32:13.893
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:26.456 --> 32:29.007
Hey, hey, hey.

32:29.453 --> 32:32.106
Look what I found.

32:33.074 --> 32:34.974
Where did you find it?

32:34.999 --> 32:37.737
In a linen bag,
stuck to the hem of a fitted sheet.

32:37.762 --> 32:39.334
<i>[poignant music]</i>

32:39.750 --> 32:42.813
That's why you quadruple check, right?

32:43.391 --> 32:45.893
Thank you, Maggie.

32:46.244 --> 32:49.229
I thought it was gone for good.

32:49.665 --> 32:53.365
Well, now it's back.

32:54.425 --> 32:55.925
Mm.

32:56.054 --> 33:01.276
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:06.285 --> 33:07.708
We're gonna beat 'em to the finish line.

33:07.733 --> 33:09.105
Here it comes. Hold on tight.

33:09.130 --> 33:10.926
- Up we go.
- Whoo!

33:10.951 --> 33:13.518
Thank you very much.

33:17.943 --> 33:20.980
Thank you again for all your help.

33:22.371 --> 33:25.446
Ms. Wechsler, can I ask you something?

33:25.472 --> 33:27.440
Sure.

33:27.688 --> 33:28.921
[sighs]

33:28.946 --> 33:31.063
You're a strong, successful woman.

33:31.783 --> 33:34.711
You flew jets.

33:35.810 --> 33:37.812
Aren't you angry with him?

33:37.837 --> 33:39.602
I tell you, Ms. Reese,

33:40.236 --> 33:44.171
some men spend their
whole lives with women

33:44.623 --> 33:48.327
but never bother to
learn what pleases them.

33:50.238 --> 33:53.879
Clyde learned.

33:53.909 --> 33:55.911
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:56.095 --> 33:57.862
Let's go, Rosebud,

33:57.887 --> 33:59.622
before this thing turns
back into a pumpkin.

33:59.647 --> 34:01.459
Thank you very much.

34:01.484 --> 34:03.485
Going flying.

34:04.087 --> 34:06.509
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:06.588 --> 34:09.322
[sighs]

34:09.690 --> 34:13.382
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:14.217 --> 34:16.705
He seems like a nice enough guy,

34:17.058 --> 34:20.706
but no one is worth lying,
cheating, or disease.

34:20.837 --> 34:23.099
Where are you getting
lying and cheating?

34:23.123 --> 34:24.358
You heard what he said.

34:24.382 --> 34:25.851
Didn't hear that.

34:25.974 --> 34:30.221
This looks like more of an...
open relationship to me.

34:30.246 --> 34:33.589
Well, you would think by
their age they'd be past that.

34:33.614 --> 34:36.592
Past wanting physical intimacy?

34:36.617 --> 34:41.161
If my boyfriend ever suggested
an open relationship,

34:41.614 --> 34:43.380
I'd kill him.

34:43.406 --> 34:44.739
Huh.

34:44.813 --> 34:46.786
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:47.053 --> 34:50.273
You might be surprised how things

34:50.297 --> 34:53.224
you once thought were so important

34:53.248 --> 34:56.011
become less so when you get older.

34:56.127 --> 35:01.333
My life definitely
become bigger, messier,

35:01.358 --> 35:04.433
far more interesting than
I ever thought it could

35:04.639 --> 35:06.251
when I was younger.

35:06.276 --> 35:07.476
And you know what?

35:07.501 --> 35:09.790
It hasn't always been such a bad thing.

35:10.133 --> 35:13.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:14.587 --> 35:17.590
Well, I'm not that young.

35:17.949 --> 35:20.650
I'm almost 26.

35:20.831 --> 35:25.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:27.363 --> 35:29.531
[huffs]

35:30.096 --> 35:34.433
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:38.504 --> 35:40.371
So you know, I was
thinking, if you guys...

35:40.396 --> 35:42.108
You know,
your friend's still going out to dinner,

35:42.133 --> 35:44.108
I wouldn't be opposed.

35:44.133 --> 35:45.843
Great, you changed your mind.

35:45.868 --> 35:47.129
Yeah, got hungry.

35:47.212 --> 35:49.781
Well, not too hungry I hope.

35:49.806 --> 35:51.044
My friend's a vegan.

35:51.069 --> 35:53.314
A vegan? And you're telling me now?

35:53.338 --> 35:54.038
That's curious.

35:54.063 --> 35:57.466
Important thing is,
it'll make Bert happy.

35:57.491 --> 35:59.726
You know I live to serve.

36:07.558 --> 36:09.358
T-shirt and a pair of jeans.

36:09.383 --> 36:10.384
I paid for it.

36:10.409 --> 36:11.408
How much?

36:11.433 --> 36:13.519
[laughter]

36:13.922 --> 36:16.255
Mr. Gleason seems much improved.

36:16.280 --> 36:17.553
Yeah.

36:18.355 --> 36:20.498
When did his tremors subside?

36:20.930 --> 36:23.047
Uh, about 20 minutes ago.

36:23.072 --> 36:24.862
And no more hallucinations?

36:25.128 --> 36:26.861
Mm-mmm.

36:26.886 --> 36:28.699
Did we up his benzos?

36:28.724 --> 36:31.263
No, why?

36:31.796 --> 36:34.998
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:35.196 --> 36:37.123
Nurse Sexton.

36:37.148 --> 36:38.298
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:39.275 --> 36:41.703
Pretty miraculous turnaround
for our frequent flier,

36:41.728 --> 36:42.706
don't you think?

36:42.731 --> 36:45.182
It looks like he'll pull through, yeah.

36:45.913 --> 36:48.895
Did you give him a drink?

36:49.114 --> 36:51.283
No.

36:51.839 --> 36:54.840
Well, someone did, so who was it?

36:55.437 --> 36:59.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:01.253 --> 37:02.928
Goodwin?

37:02.953 --> 37:06.241
I guess once a nurse, always a nurse.

37:06.730 --> 37:13.394
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:15.664 --> 37:17.600
Excuse me, a word, please?

37:17.625 --> 37:19.626
Sure.

37:19.651 --> 37:21.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.220 --> 37:24.389
You gave Mr. Gleason a drink?

37:24.414 --> 37:26.660
He was likely going to die without one.

37:26.685 --> 37:27.683
I've seen it happen.

37:27.708 --> 37:29.474
So it doesn't matter if that
was against hospital policy,

37:29.499 --> 37:31.105
'cause I'm pretty sure if that were me,

37:31.130 --> 37:33.383
I'd be raked over the
coals right now by you.

37:33.408 --> 37:35.375
Damned if you do and
damned if you don't.

37:35.400 --> 37:37.935
I admit, it's a bit
of a double standard.

37:37.960 --> 37:38.939
What can I say?

37:38.964 --> 37:41.706
This patient...

37:42.645 --> 37:44.513
he had a chance to kick his addiction.

37:44.538 --> 37:45.944
Now it's gone.

37:45.969 --> 37:49.896
Dr. Halstead,
an addict doesn't just kick a habit.

37:49.922 --> 37:52.068
He's got to want to quit,
and right now he doesn't.

37:52.125 --> 37:56.130
Listen, you can't force a
person to move on from something

37:56.155 --> 37:58.070
if they're not ready.

37:58.830 --> 38:02.133
You know they found Dr. Manning's ring.

38:02.682 --> 38:05.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:07.720 --> 38:10.341
Want to come up with me to see her?

38:10.888 --> 38:13.724
I'll be up a little later.

38:14.750 --> 38:20.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:21.986 --> 38:25.022
Any shortness of breath?

38:29.167 --> 38:33.515
Mr. McCormick, I am sorry.

38:33.778 --> 38:35.612
We were just trying to deal
with the circumstances...

38:35.637 --> 38:36.902
The best you could.

38:36.949 --> 38:39.586
I know.

38:42.607 --> 38:46.585
Do you even think about
God's will or just your own?

38:48.419 --> 38:53.187
You familiar with...  Peter 5:2?

38:53.892 --> 38:56.663
"Be a shepherd to the flock
that is under your care.

38:56.688 --> 38:58.470
"Watch over them.

38:59.810 --> 39:01.811
"Not for what you'll get out of it,

39:01.836 --> 39:04.462
but because you are eager to serve God."

39:11.005 --> 39:12.598
You entrusted me to watch over

39:12.623 --> 39:14.724
not just your body but your soul.

39:15.578 --> 39:17.676
You're alive... .

39:18.335 --> 39:21.532
because I couldn't
imagine life without you.

39:25.070 --> 39:27.488
I misplaced my faith.

39:28.183 --> 39:31.629
Today, I didn't serve God.

39:32.648 --> 39:35.650
But I have to believe that a god of love

39:35.770 --> 39:38.847
is also a god of forgiveness.

39:55.738 --> 39:58.910
<i>[solemn music]</i>

39:59.955 --> 40:06.908
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:18.332 --> 40:22.385
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:36.629 --> 40:39.465
[chuckles]

40:39.490 --> 40:41.491
[sighs]

40:41.801 --> 40:45.768
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:09.932 --> 41:15.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

